* if there's no event running, schedule one
* else if there's a running event, and the new timeout is greater than the current one, just update m_end (the Expire function will do the rest)
* else if there's a running event, but the new timeout is lesser than the current one, cancel the current event and schedule a new one (because the Expire function would be fired too late).

Probably the 2nd check could be simplified in:
```cpp
  else if (delayUntileExpiration >= delay) // event will be delayed
    {
      m_end = std::max(end, m_end);
    }

```

This doesn't seem to match the docs:  the delay argument should be the new remaining time, no matter what the old `m_end` value was (otherwise there's no way to set the new end between m_event and m_end.

In other words, this line should just be

    m_end = end;

I know `Timer` does it the way you have now, but IMO this would be more direct:

    template <typename FN, typename... Ts>
    SetFunction (FN fn, Ts&&... args);

Not only you're right, this does simplify the code by a great length.

Now the function is:
```cpp
void
SmartEvent::SetNewExpiration (Time delay)
{
  NS_LOG_FUNCTION (this << delay);
  Time end = Now () + delay;
  Time delayUntilExpiration = Simulator::GetDelayLeft (m_event);

  m_cancelled = false;
  m_end = end;

  if (!m_event.IsRunning ()) // No pending event, create one
    {
      m_event = Simulator::Schedule (delay, &SmartEvent::Expire, this);
    }
  else if (delay < delayUntilExpiration) // Event scheduled before the end of the actual one -  it must be recreated
    {
      m_event.Cancel ();
      m_event = Simulator::Schedule (delay, &SmartEvent::Expire, this);
    }
  return;
}
```

